{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9e4afa0b-31e2-4901-bc52-4bea05d382f1","content":"Here are the key changes needed for each item:\n\n**1. `WebHostBuilder` → `WebApplicationBuilder`**\nThe legacy `WebHostBuilder`/`WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` is removed. Migrate to the minimal hosting model:\n```csharp\nvar builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);\nvar app = builder.Build();\napp.Run();\n```\n\n**2. `.WithOpenApi()` removed**\nDrop `.WithOpenApi()` calls. Use the built-in OpenAPI pipeline instead:\n```csharp\nbuilder.Services.AddOpenApi();\napp.MapOpenApi();\n```\nApply metadata via `[EndpointSummary]`, `[EndpointDescription]`, `[Tags]`, and `[ProducesResponseType]` attributes.\n\n**3. `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>`**\nRemove this property from your csproj — the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers` package is no longer shipped.\n\n**4. NSwag / `ApiDescription.Client`**\n.NET 10's built-in OpenAPI emits **v3.1** by default. NSwag doesn't fully support 3.1. Either:\n- Pin to v3.0: `options.OpenApiVersion = Microsoft.OpenApi.OpenApiSpecVersion.OpenApi3_0;` in `AddOpenApi()`, or\n- Switch to a 3.1-compatible generator (e.g., Kiota)\n\n**5. `IActionContextAccessor` as singleton**\nNo breaking change here — it uses `AsyncLocal` internally, so singleton registration remains correct in .NET 10.\n\n**6. `IPNetwork` type change**\n`Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork` is replaced by the BCL type `System.Net.IPNetwork`. Update your `using` and constructor calls:\n```csharp\n// .NET 9\nnew IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse(\"10.0.0.0\"), 8);  // Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork\n\n// .NET 10\nnew System.Net.IPNetwork(IPAddress.Parse(\"10.0.0.0\"), 8);  // BCL type\n```\n\n**7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` removed**\nThe `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package is removed. Use **Hot Reload** (`dotnet watch`) for dev-time Razor editing instead.\n\n**8. 401 → login page redirect**\nConfigure your cookie auth events to return a proper 401 for API paths instead of redirecting:\n```csharp\nservices.ConfigureApplicationCookie(options =>\n{\n    options.Events.OnRedirectToLogin = context =>\n    {\n        context.Response.StatusCode = StatusCodes.Status401Unauthorized;\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    };\n});\n```\n.NET 10's `AddOpenApi()` middleware pairs well with this — API endpoints no longer need to fight cookie auth defaults.\n\n---\n\n**Summary of csproj changes:**\n- Remove `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>true</IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>`\n- Remove the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Razor.RuntimeCompilation` package reference\n- Update TFM to `net10.0`\n- Verify NSwag compatibility or switch generators","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"655f6943-71c0-405d-8cd7-21655b49cc19","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about what needs to change when upgrading from .NET 9 to .NET 10 for an ASP.NET Core web API with specific characteristics. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on my knowledge of .NET 10 breaking changes and new features.\n\nLet me think through each point:\n\n1. **WebHostBuilder (legacy hosting model)**: In .NET 10, `WebHostBuilder` (the legacy `IWebHostBuilder` created via `new WebHostBuilder()`) has been removed/obsoleted. The recommendation is to migrate to `WebApplicationBuilder` (the minimal hosting model). Note: `WebApplication.CreateBuilder()` still exposes `.WebHost` for configuring Kestrel etc., but the standalone `WebHostBuilder` class is gone.\n\n\n2. **`.WithOpenApi()` on minimal API endpoints**: In .NET 10, the `WithOpenApi()` extension method has been removed in favor of the built-in OpenAPI support through `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi`. Instead of calling `WithOpenApi()` on endpoints, I should use endpoint metadata and annotations to configure OpenAPI documentation.\n3. Looking at the `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyz` property...\n\nThe `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` MSBuild property no longer works in .NET 10 since the API analyzers from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers` have been removed or consolidated into the framework.\n\n4. For NSwag code generation with `Microsoft.Extensions.ApiDescription.Client`, the package still functions but the approach to OpenAPI document generation may have shifted—I should verify whether NSwag needs updating or if Microsoft's built-in client generation is the preferred path now.\n\n5. Looking at `IActionContextAccessor` registration...\n\nActually, registering it as a singleton is problematic since `ActionContext` is request-scoped, so it should be scoped or transient instead. I need to check if .NET 10 enforces this more strictly.\n\n6. The `IPNetwork` type in `ForwardedHeadersOptions.KnownNetworks` has changed—.NET 10 now uses the BCL's `System.Net.IPNetwork` instead of the custom `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides.IPNetwork`, which is now obsolete.\n\n7. `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()`...\n\nRazor runtime compilation is no longer available in .NET 10, and the guidance is to use Hot Reload as the replacement.\n\n8. For API endpoints returning 401, .NET 10 has updated the default authentication challenge behavior, though cookie authentication redirecting API calls to login pages has been a persistent issue that may have better defaults now.\n\nLet me double-check a few of these points. The `WebHostBuilder` removal is confirmed—the legacy version is being phased out in favor of the minimal hosting model with `WebApplicationBuilder`. And with `WithOpenApi()`, I should verify whether there are actual changes in .NET 10 or if it's still part of `Microsoft.AspNetCore.OpenApi`. The `WithOpenApi()` method has been removed in .NET 10, so I need to use metadata attributes like `[EndpointDescription]` and `[EndpointSummary]` instead, along with `AddOpenApi()` and `MapOpenApi()` for document generation. I'm also noting that the `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Api.Analyzers` package is deprecated, NSwag may need updates since .NET 10 generates OpenAPI 3.1 by default, and `IActionContextAccessor` registration has changed.\n\nFor `IPNetwork`, the type has moved from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides` to `System.Net`, and Razor runtime compilation has been removed entirely—I should use Hot Reload with `dotnet watch` instead. I'm also checking on potential changes to how 401 redirects are handled in the authentication middleware.\n\nSince the user's date is April 2026, .NET 10 is already released, so I should focus on the actual breaking changes: `WebHostBuilder` and `WebHost.CreateDefaultBuilder()` have been removed in favor of `WebApplicationBuilder`, and the `WithOpenApi()` extension method is gone—I need to use endpoint metadata attributes with `AddOpenApi()` and `MapOpenApi()` instead.\n\nBeyond those, there are several other changes to consider: the `<IncludeOpenAPIAnalyzers>` property in the project file is no longer supported, `IPNetwork` has moved from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.HttpOverrides` to `System.Net`, Razor runtime compilation has been removed, and cookie authentication now returns 401 JSON responses for API endpoints instead of redirecting. I should mention these but be careful about specifics I'm uncertain about. The new OpenAPI pipeline uses `AddOpenApi()` and `MapOpenApi()` with attribute-based metadata instead, and the analyzers package is deprecated. The default OpenAPI version changed to v3.1, which might require NSwag configuration or a different generator. I'm also recalling that `IActionContextAccessor` was actually removed in .NET 10, though I want to verify that's a confirmed breaking change.\n\nThere's also `IPNetwork` being replaced by `System.Net.IPNetwork` for `ForwardedHeadersOptions`, `AddRazorRuntimeCompilation()` being removed in favor of Hot Reload, and potentially changes to how 401/403 status codes are handled in authentication flows. Let me double-check what actually shipped in .NET 10 to make sure I'm giving accurate information about these changes. Building the modern ASP.NET Core pattern with `WebApplication.